<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-08-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-08-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="126" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d126">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00/15870½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. W. J. Bryan to the Secretary of State</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Ossawotomie, Kans</hi>.</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-08-16">
                                    <hi rend="italic">August 16, 1915</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>
                        </p>
                        <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                        <p>Have just read your note to Austria. It is very conclusive and I am
                            telegraphing an editorial endorsement of it to the <hi rend="italic">Commoner</hi>, but it may be too late for this month’s issue. Am
                            glad you are restraining the jingoes on the Mexican border.</p>
                        <p>We have enjoyed reading the complimentary notices of Mrs. Lansing and
                            yourself.</p>
                        <p>With kindest regards [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>